<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="C19.S27">
<title>Asymptotic Approximations and Expansions</title>          
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS1">
<title>Notation</title>         
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C19.S27.SS1.p1.s1">
Throughout this section <Math equation-number="19.27.1" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E1">a=\tfrac{1}{2}(x+y),b=\tfrac{1}{2}(y+z),c=\tfrac{1}{3}(x+y+z),f=(xyz)^{1/3},g=(xy)^{1/2},h=(yz)^{1/2}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS2">
<title><Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.m1">R_{F}\left(x,y,z\right)</Math></title>         
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1.s1">
Assume <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1.m1">x</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1.m2">y</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1.m3">z</Math> are real and nonnegative and at most one of them is 0.Then <Math equation-number="19.27.2" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E2">R_{F}\left(x,y,z\right)=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{z}}\left(\ln\frac{8z}{a+g}\right)\left (1+O\left(\frac{a}{z}\right)\right), if a/z\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C19.S27.SS2.p1.s2">
 <Math equation-number="19.27.3" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E3">R_{F}\left(x,y,z\right)=R_{F}\left(0,y,z\right)-\frac{1}{\sqrt{h}}\left(\sqrt{ \frac{x}{h}}+O\left(\frac{x}{h}\right)\right), if x/h\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS3">
<title><Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.m1">R_{G}\left(x,y,z\right)</Math></title>         
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.s1">
Assume <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.m1">x</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.m2">y</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.m3">z</Math> are real and nonnegative and at most one of them is 0. Then <Math equation-number="19.27.4" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E4">R_{G}\left(x,y,z\right)=\frac{\sqrt{z}}{2}\left(1+O\left(\frac{a}{z}\ln\frac{z }{a}\right)\right), if a/z\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.s2">
 <Math equation-number="19.27.5" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E5">R_{G}\left(x,y,z\right)=R_{G}\left(0,y,z\right)+\sqrt{x}O\left(\sqrt{x/h} \right), if x/h\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C19.S27.SS3.p1.s3">
 <Math equation-number="19.27.6" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E6">R_{G}\left(0,y,z\right)={\frac{\sqrt{z}}{2}+\frac{y}{8\sqrt{z}}\left(\ln\left( \frac{16z}{y}\right)-1\right)\*\left(1+O\left(\frac{y}{z}\right)\right)}, if y/z\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS4">
<title><Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.m1">R_{D}\left(x,y,z\right)</Math></title>        
 
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.s1">
Assume <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.m1">x</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.m2">y</Math> are real and nonnegative, at most one of them is 0, and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.m3">z&gt;0</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.s2">
Then <Math equation-number="19.27.7" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E7">R_{D}\left(x,y,z\right)=\frac{3}{2z^{3/2}}\left(\ln\left(\frac{8z}{a+g}\right) -2\right)\left(1+O\left(\frac{a}{z}\right)\right), if a/z\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.s3">
<Math equation-number="19.27.8" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E8">R_{D}\left(x,y,z\right)=\frac{3}{\sqrt{xyz}}-\frac{6}{xy}R_{G}\left(x,y,0 \right)\left(1+O\left(\frac{z}{g}\right)\right), if z/g\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.s4">
<Math equation-number="19.27.9" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E9">R_{D}\left(x,y,z\right)=\frac{3}{\sqrt{xz}(\sqrt{y}+\sqrt{z})}\left(1+O\left( \frac{b}{x}\ln\frac{x}{b}\right)\right), if b/x\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C19.S27.SS4.p1.s5">
<Math equation-number="19.27.10" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E10">R_{D}\left(x,y,z\right)=R_{D}\left(0,y,z\right)-\frac{3\sqrt{x}}{hz}\left(1+O \left(\sqrt{\frac{x}{h}}\right)\right), if x/h\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS5">
<title><Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.m1">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)</Math></title>         
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s1">
Assume <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.m1">x</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.m2">y</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.m3">z</Math> are real and nonnegative, at most one of them is 0, and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.m4">p&gt;0</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s2">
Then <Math equation-number="19.27.11" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E11">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)={\frac{3}{p}R_{F}\left(x,y,z\right)-\frac{3\pi}{2p^{ 3/2}}\left(1+O\left(\sqrt{\frac{c}{p}}\right)\right)}, if c/p\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s3">
<Math equation-number="19.27.12" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E12">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)={\frac{3}{2\sqrt{xyz}}\left(\ln\left(\frac{4f}{p} \right)-2\right)\left(1+O\left(\frac{p}{f}\right)\right)}, if p/f\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s4">
<Math equation-number="19.27.13" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E13">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)=\frac{3}{2\sqrt{z}p}\left(\ln\left(\frac{8z}{a+g} \right)-2\!R_{C}\left(1,\frac{p}{z}\right)+O\left(\left(\frac{a}{z}+\frac{a}{p }\right)\ln\frac{p}{a}\right)\right), if \max(x,y)/\min(z,p)\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s5">
<Math equation-number="19.27.14" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E14">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)=\frac{3}{\sqrt{yz}}R_{C}\left(x,p\right)-\frac{6}{yz }R_{G}\left(0,y,z\right)+O\left(\frac{\sqrt{x+2p}}{yz}\right), if \max(x,p)/\min(y,z)\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="6" sentence-num-in-section="17" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s6">
<Math equation-number="19.27.15" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E15">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)=R_{J}\left(0,y,z,p\right)-\frac{3\sqrt{x}}{hp}\left( 1+O\left(\left(\frac{b}{h}+\frac{h}{p}\right)\sqrt{\frac{x}{h}}\right)\right), if x/\min(y,z,p)\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="7" sentence-num-in-section="18" xml:id="C19.S27.SS5.p1.s7">
<Math equation-number="19.27.16" mode="display" xml:id="C19.S27.E16">R_{J}\left(x,y,z,p\right)=(3/\sqrt{x})R_{C}\left((h+p)^{2},2(b+h)p\right)+O \left(\frac{1}{x^{3/2}}\ln\frac{x}{b+h}\right), if \max(y,z,p)/x\to 0.</Math>
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C19.S27.SS6">
<title>Asymptotic Expansions</title>         
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="19" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p1.s1">
The approximations in §§19.27(i)–19.27(v)arefurnished with upper and lower bounds by Carlson and Gustafson (1994), sometimes with two or three approximations of differing accuracies.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="20" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p1.s2">
Although they are obtained (with some exceptions) by approximating uniformly the integrand of each elliptic integral, some occur also as the leading terms of known asymptotic series with error bounds (Wong (1983, §4),Carlson and Gustafson (1985), López (2000, 2001)).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="21" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p1.s3">
These series converge but not fast enough, given the complicated nature of their terms, to be very useful in practice.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="22" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p2.s1">
A similar (but more general) situation prevails for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p2.m1">R_{-a}\left(\mathbf{b};\mathbf{z}\right)</Math> when some of the variables <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C19.S27.SS6.p2.m2">z_{1},\dots,z_{n}</Math> are smaller in magnitude than the rest;see Carlson (1985, (4.16)–(4.19)and (2.26)–(2.29)).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
</section>
